To be able to tell nodes apart, we need to assign a unique identifier to each node, which we'll refer to as an index."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"6B8fRcx9S70H"},"source":["![Screenshot 2021-10-15 at 16.11.38.png](data:image/png;base64,)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"XbiWvdB2TG6p"},"source":["Each edge is defined by the nodes it connects, and is therefore represented as a pair (or tuple) of nodes. If the graph is explicitly undirected, the order of the nodes in the pair is not important, but in a directed graph the edge $(u, v)$ is different from the edge $(v, u)$. A common way of representing graphs is to always assume that it's a directed graph, and to represent undirected graphs by adding the edge in both directions. A real world example of this directed graph would be e.g a follower graph on a social network.\n","\n","In many cases, the relationship _is_ symmetric, so $(1,2)$ _is_ the same as $(2,1)$. We will refer to this property as _permutation invariance_, changing the order of the nodes in the edge of an undirected graph is still the exact same graph."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"TN6vrBVbAxdC"},"source":["## Permutation invariance in python\n","Below is a figure of an undirected graph followed by python code representing this datastructures)?**"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"-gRj-gf2MQKK"},"source":["# The Adjacency matrix\n","We've represented the graph as a list of edges, but another common representation is that of an _adjacency matrix_. Since an edge essentially represents a pairwise relationship, we can encode these relationships in a matrix $A$ of size $\\text{number of nodes} \\times \\text{number of nodes}$, where each element $A_{i,j}$ encodes the relationshop between these nodes. When this matrix encodes the edge relationships, we typically set the positions representing an edge to $1$ and the positions representing pairs without edges to $0$.\n","\n","The adjecancy matrix will play a central role in our later discussions on Graph Neural Networks and Transformers.\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"-8Dm6Qzx8gM9"},"source":["![Screenshot 2021-10-15 at Create a graph representation below\n","town_nodes = {...}\n","town_edges = {...}"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"n0btz-VGO5_t"},"source":["# From dictionaries to tensors\n","The dictionary representation we use above is straight forward, but not suitable for neural networks. In a neural network we want to represent everything as vectors or n-dimensional arrays. This means we have to _encode_ our graph information. \n","\n","## The graph structure\n","We have already seen how the structure of the graph (the edges) can be readily represented by an adjacency matrix, and this format will suit us well when we implement our graph neural network. \n","\n","## Node and edge attributes\n","We've seen above how nodes and edges can have attributes of different kind. For the purpose of a neural network there is two main attribute types we need to keep separate: _discrete_ and _continuous_.\n","\n","### Continuous variable\n","Continuous variables are numerical and can take any value in some range (e.g. negative to positive infinity). For neural networks we typically just use them they are (perhaps performing some standardization pre-processing), and might concatenate them if we have multiple such attributes.\n","\n","### Discrete variables\n","A discrete variable takes a value (referred to as _level_) from a finite set, in the examples above we saw colour, atom type, bond type, experience and ratings, etc. In neural networks we have to treat _categorical_ variables in a special way, these are discrete variables which are not ordinal (can't be compared with inequalities). We represent them using _embeddings_, dense numerical vectors of high dimension (>100). Each _level_ of the categorical variable is associated with its own distinct vector, it's _embedding_.\n","\n","These embeddings are almost always _learned parameters_, just like the weights of our neural networks, and should be considered part of the model.\n","\n","In neural network frameworks such as pytorch, a requirement for this is that we know beforehand how many levels of the variable there are, so that we can create this mapping."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"PlQLLCK3o16l"},"source":["![caffeine_graph.png](data:image/png;base64,)"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":329,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637611929368,"user":{"displayName":"Erik categorical values, we've translated them to the universal language of integers. Treating them as just numerical values and inputting them to a neural network layer _as is_ would make learning hard. It would tell the neural network that levels encoded to similar values are similar, which often is wrong.\n","\n","Instead, we associate each integer value with a numerical vector: an _embedding_.\n","\n","**note: it is often taught that categorical values should be represented by  one-hot vectors. For contemporary neural network frameworks this is bad practice. Encode them as integers and use embedding layers.**"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"uHQvvCyDogER"},"source":["## Roll our own embeddings\n","To get a sense of how embedding might work, we'll start by creating our own. Later we will use the `torch.nn.Embedding` module instead. In our home-made embeddings, we just create a matrix of as many rows as there are levels of our categorical variable, and as many columns as we'd like. The rows will be called `num_embeddings` since they tell us how many distinct embedding vectors there are. The columns is `embedding_dim` a hyper parameter similar to the size of a neural network layer, the higher, the more capacity our embedding layer will have."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"qdc4XUpmq4fC"},"outputs":[],"source":["import torch"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":9,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637611965491,"user":{"displayName":"Erik Ylipää","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Ghv2ZnBVJIOqdwt_HBhCMHTtEbc2FUGzMgmKQEW7VE=s64","userId":"10747062110949017925"},"user_tz":-60},"id":"E96QoN08oy3N","outputId":"1b6892b8-1062-4163-c72e-f8fa0145ad5f"},"outputs":[],"source":["enc_caffeine_nodes"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":310,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637612003565,"user":{"displayName":"Erik Ylipää","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Ghv2ZnBVJIOqdwt_HBhCMHTtEbc2FUGzMgmKQEW7VE=s64","userId":"10747062110949017925"},"user_tz":-60},"id":"wRF689OkpCMA","outputId":"a44f4341-b663-483b-ebc6-962e15046ad5"},"outputs":[],"source":["num_embeddings = len(ATOM_TYPES)\n","embedding_dim = 16  # For now if we just make sure that we use the same order here as in the edge features things will work out fine."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":302,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637612049083,"user":{"displayName":"Erik Ylipää","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Ghv2ZnBVJIOqdwt_HBhCMHTtEbc2FUGzMgmKQEW7VE=s64","userId":"10747062110949017925"},"user_tz":-60},"id":"GAcTkefisPwq","outputId":"f2847b70-3cc9-471a-a68b-8897d682b36a"},"outputs":[],"source":["caffeine_node_features_stack = dict()\n","for node_idx, embedded_features in sorted(embedded_caffeine_nodes.items()):  \n","  for variable_name, embedding in embedded_features.items():\n","    # Using a defaultdict(list) is neater here, but this should be more familiar\n","    if variable_name not in caffeine_node_features_stack:\n","      caffeine_node_features_stack[variable_name] = []\n","    caffeine_node_features_stack[variable_name].append(embedding)\n","\n","# Now we've gathered the embeddings and we'll stack them to create our features\n","stacked_node_features = dict()\n","for variable_name, stack in caffeine_node_features_stack.items():  \n","  feature_tensor = torch.stack(stack)\n","  stacked_node_features[variable_name] = feature_tensor\n","\n","stacked_node_features\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"7eS3u-hKALj4"},"source":["### Change order of operations\n","We now have a node feature matrix which is very well suited for input to our nerual network, but we performed a lot of simple operations to get there. Most of our python-based frameworks prefer it if we do multiple things in paralell, and going from integer codes to embeddings is a great example of that."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":301,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637622665223,"user":{"displayName":"Erik Ylipää","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Ghv2ZnBVJIOqdwt_HBhCMHTtEbc2FUGzMgmKQEW7VE=s64","userId":"10747062110949017925"},"user_tz":-60},"id":"jl4WY32SBPDs","outputId":"3a04f081-8a28-4dda-9e7f-324280ba7e7d"},"outputs":[],"source":["enc_caffeine_nodes_stack = {'atom_type': []}\n","for node_idx, node_attributes in sym_caffeine_nodes.items():\n","  sym_atom_type = node_attributes['atom_type']\n","  encoded_atom_type = ATOM_TYPES[sym_atom_type]\n","  enc_caffeine_nodes_stack['atom_type'].append(encoded_atom_type)\n","enc_caffeine_nodes_stack\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":4,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637622666168,"user":{"displayName":"Erik Ylipää","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Ghv2ZnBVJIOqdwt_HBhCMHTtEbc2FUGzMgmKQEW7VE=s64","userId":"10747062110949017925"},"user_tz":-60},"id":"h2njkCCmBIsy","outputId":"254b1a54-bb36-4034-e58c-620201d4065e"},"outputs":[],"source":["emb_caffeine_nodes_stack = {}\n","for variable_name, encoded_stack in enc_caffeine_nodes_stack.items():\n","  enc_tensor = torch.tensor(encoded_stack, dtype=torch.long) # It's important to have a long type here for later\n","  emb_tensor = ATOM_TYPE_EMBEDDINGS[enc_tensor]  # We can just use the vector to index the rows, nothing more fancy is necessary\n","  emb_caffeine_nodes_stack[variable_name] = emb_tensor\n","emb_caffeine_nodes_stack"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"y-cM32cIFSc_"},"source":["You now have implemented the operation below. Each node is associated with a feature vector which is stacked into a 2d array."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"OogAniBNFNGp"},"source":["![erik_2 (Small).png](data:image/png;base64,)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"uR4NBuu9CsnI"},"source":["### Edge features\n","\n","The node features are straight forward, since we can just stack the vectors according to the order of the node labels.\n","\n","For the edge features is a bit more complicated, we can't just do away with the pairwise information. There are two ways of dealing with this, either keep the information about what nodes the edge correspond to in a separate tensor, and the feature vector in a similar tensor as for the node features.\n","\n","The other option is to use the same strategy as for the adjacency matrix: encode all pairwise relationships with a \"matrix\", but where each element of this \"matrix\" is actually a feature vector, so it's actually a 3d array.\n","\n","So if we have the edges between nodes $i,j$ with features $\\mathbf{h}_{i,j}$:\n","\n","$$\n","\\{1,2\\}: \\mathbf{h}_{1,2}\\\\\n","\\{2,3\\}: \\mathbf{h}_{2,3}\\\\\n","\\{2,4\\}: \\mathbf{h}_{2,4}\\\\\n","\\{3,4\\}: \\mathbf{h}_{3,4}\\\\\n","$$\n","\n","We can represent this with a edge feature 3-tensor like this:\n","\n","$$\\begin{bmatrix}\n","\\mathbf{0}& \\mathbf{h}_{1,2}& \\mathbf{0}& \\mathbf{0}\\\\\n","\\mathbf{h}_{1,2}& \\mathbf{0}& \\mathbf{h}_{2,3}& \\mathbf{h}_{2,4}\\\\\n","\\mathbf{0}& \\mathbf{h}_{2,3}& \\mathbf{0}& \\mathbf{h}_{3,4}\\\\\n","\\mathbf{0}& \\mathbf{h}_{2,4}& \\mathbf{h}_{3,4}& \\mathbf{0}\\\\\n","\\end{bmatrix}$$\n","\n","Pairwise relationships which are missing use the $0$-vector, we call this a _padding_ value.\n","\n","This representation might seem really wasteful, and for sparse graphs it will be, but in this workshop we wan't to see how we can go from Graph Neural Netorks to Tranformers, where it makes much more sense.\n","\n","Below is a figure which illustrates this idea."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"IcKXtxMWIOmM"},"source":["![stacked_edge_features (Small).png](data:image/png;base64,)"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"YvkoVoj5RhlQ"},"outputs":[],"source":["caffeine_nodes = sym_caffeine_nodes.keys()\n","n_nodes = 2 axises\n","caffeine_nodes_indices = {node_idx: i for i, node_idx in enumerate(sorted(caffeine_nodes))}\n","\n","caffeine_edge_features_tensor = torch.zeros((n_nodes, n_nodes, embedding_dim), If we just extend what we've done so far it can be a bit messy, so we'll use classes to organize the pipeline. Below is a figure which illustrates this pipeline\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"qfNzacyAjOQe"},"source":["\n","\n","![Screenshot 2021-10-15 at 11.09.10.png](data:image/png;base64,)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"Wx7e_EUDcg7A"},"source":["### Feature book keeping\n","\n","Consider this code fragment: \n","```python\n","enc_caffeine_nodes = {}\n","for node_idx, node_attributes in sym_caffeine_nodes.items():\n","  sym_atom_type = node_attributes['atom_type']\n","  encoded_atom_type = ATOM_TYPES[sym_atom_type]\n","  enc_caffeine_nodes[node_idx] = {'atom_type': encoded_atom_type}\n","```\n","\n","This code takes a node feature and encodes it, but right now it hardcodes the node features ('atom_type') and the encoding dictionary (ATOM_TYPES) for the symbolic features. We're going to encapsulate these values inside a class, which will essentally act as a _type_ for our features. This class will be used instead of the string key we've used to build our features, allowing us to always have access to the feature metadata we need.\n","\n","Below we introduce a `ContinuousVariable` and `CategoricalVariable`. The first one is essentially just there for completeness sake, the important one is the categorical variable."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"qTJT7fBoebmb"},"source":["### **Question: look at the `CategoricalVariable` class below. What is the purpose of the argument `add_null_value`?**\n","\n","Hint: Have a look at the `PADDED_BOND_TYPES` above, what did we do there and why?"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"7vibS4tAca3h"},"outputs":[],"source":["class ContinuousVariable:\n","  def __init__(self, name):\n","    self.name = name\n","\n","  def __repr__(self):\n","    return f'<ContinuousFeature: {self.name}>'\n","\n","  def __eq__(self, other):\n","    return self.name == other.name\n","\n","  def __hash__(self):\n","    return hash(self.name)\n","\n","\n","class CategoricalVariable:\n","  def __init__(self, name, values, add_null_value=True):\n","    self.name = name\n","    self.has_null_value = add_null_value\n","    if self.has_null_value:\n","      self.null_value = None\n","      values = (None,) + tuple(values)\n","    self.values = tuple(values)\n","    self.value_to_idx_mapping = {v: i for i, v in enumerate(values)}\n","    self.inv_value_to_idx_mapping = {i: v for v, i in\n","                                     self.value_to_idx_mapping.items()}\n","    \n","    if self.has_null_value:\n","      self.null_value_idx = self.value_to_idx_mapping[self.null_value]\n","  \n","  def get_null_idx(self):\n","    if self.has_null_value:\n","      return self.null_value_idx\n","    else:\n","      raise RuntimeError(f\"Categorical variable {self.name} has no null value\")\n","\n","  def value_to_idx(self, value):\n","    return self.value_to_idx_mapping[value]\n","  \n","  def idx_to_value(self, idx):\n","    return self.inv_value_to_idx_mapping[idx]\n","  \n","  def __len__(self):\n","    return len(self.values)\n","  \n","  def __repr__(self):\n","    return f'<CategoricalFeature: {self.name}>'\n","\n","  def __eq__(self, other):\n","    return self.name == other.name and self.values == other.values\n","\n","  def __hash__(self):\n","    return hash((self.name, self.values))"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"zd6vau41ialU"},"source":["You might be wandering what all the extra methods do (`__hash__` and `__eq__` in particular). They are there to allow us to compare objects of these classes with each others in meaningful ways. This is not directly relevant to the workshop, but makes these objects behave as intendend even if they are copied when we use multiprocessing"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":304,"status":"ok","timestamp":1637616702364,"user":{"displayName":"Erik We create two different instances of the variable, but with the same content\n","a = CategoricalVariable('foo', [1,2,3])\n","b = CategoricalVariable('foo', [1,2,3])\n","# If we didn't implement __eq__ and __hash__, the `is` operator would be used \n","# for key lookups in dictionaries\n","print(\"a is b?\", a is b) \n","print(\"a == b?\", a == b)\n","foo_dict = {a: 'bar'}\n","# Without __hash__, the dict access below would give a KeyError\n","print('foo_dict[b] ==\\'{}\\''.format(foo_dict[b]))"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"77By2WnGziiH"},"source":["### Encoding multiple process of first encoding graphs in clear python objects and then dived into how to model node and edge attributes. We looked at how these attributes needs to be treated separately if they are categorical, and how we can use embeddings to represent the levels of the categorical variable as dense vectors suitable for inputs to a neural network.\n"," We also looked at how we might combine multiple attributes per node and edge, and how this requires us to keep track of the possible levels of the different variables as well as separate `Embeddings` for them.\n","\n"," Important concepts:\n","  - Adjacency matrix\n","  - Categorical variable\n","  - Embedding\n","  - Symbolic to integer index mapping\n","  - Padding value\n","  - Permutation invariance"]}],"metadata":{"colab":{"authorship_tag":"ABX9TyPyulhVtu1YHrJAdSux9wx7","collapsed_sections":[],"name":"1a_representing_graphs_for_neural_networks.ipynb","provenance":[],"toc_visible":true},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}
